                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="color: darkblue"><span style="font-size: 18px; line-height: normal">Fading&#8217;s Plane of Mischief Charming Guide</span></span>
<br />
	<span style="font-style: italic">A guide to Plane of Mischief charming for enchanters level 53+ in the courtyard area. Aimed towards modest geared enchanters in the high 50&#8217;s to low 60&#8217;s, from beginner to moderate levels of charming experience.</span>
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">DISCLAIMER</span></span>
<br />
 I make no guarantees on this charming guide. It&#8217;s just here to share what I have learned in this gem of a zone for charming in levels 53+. First of all, let me say that I am currently level 63 with 140+ AA&#8217;s (currently Total Domination 2), but I began charming here at about 56. I have my epic which helps a lot for charming. Most of the rest of my gear is below elemental, and very modest. I&#8217;m gonna write this for the non raiding, non-uber geared enchanter in mind. So all you ubers, please, don&#8217;t laugh at us! We&#8217;re trying.  I&#8217;ll try to explain spell line-ups and strategies and also give alternatives as there are many variations in charming tactics. If anyone feels they have info to add, please feel free to email me at the address at the bottom. So, without further delay, here is how I do it. It&#8217;s not the only way, and I&#8217;m sure there are others who have preferred ways. I have also tried this with a duoing partner, usually a druid, but also a wizard or ranger work well. Other combinations I have tried are cleric, sk, pally and mage, though it&#8217;s difficult getting to know each other. In general, with a duoing druid, the experience flows like water. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">BEFORE GOING:</span></span>
<br />

<br />
I, myself, generally don&#8217;t grab anything before I head to PoM, but I know here are a few suggestions to help out in areas which you may or may not be lacking.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Run Speed:</span>
<br />
1)	Grab a wolf form in PoK if you have Perm. Illusion.
<br />
2)	Or Grab SoW potions
<br />
3)	For me, I have RunSpeed3, so I generally don&#8217;t worry about it. My charming technique doesn&#8217;t involve a lot of running, so for me it&#8217;s not necessary
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Tribute:</span>
<br />
1)	If you are lacking (as I am) in Mana Preservation, Improved Damage or Mana Regen items, tribute is a great way to boost these. And now, use can set what you want to turn on at the Tribute Master, and turn it off or on when you need it (in 10 minute clumps at least).
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Components:</span>
<br />
	1)   Peridots (for those that don&#8217;t have Arcane Rune yet)
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Pet Gear: </span>
<br />
1)	I personally don&#8217;t use them, again due to my technique, but with varying tactics, you could grab these.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Additional Gear:</span>
<br />
1)	Epic. This helps a lot. I don&#8217;t have to mem a haste spell and it makes my pet mean!
<br />
2)	Blue Ceramic Band. Get it. Don&#8217;t charm without it! Saves mana and makes sure you don&#8217;t lose out on that exp.
<br />
3)	Unfortunately I do NOT have an clicky invis item. But, if you have one, I can imagine it is wonderful. It would definitely be nice to free up that spell slot for something else. Not necessary, but worth it.
<br />
4)	CHA gear. Discussion on this can be found all over. I have found that yes CHA DOES help in charming. Mines maxed.
<br />
5)	Focus Items: I don&#8217;t have any, but Extended Range is a good one(Supple Scale Armband comes to mind). Also Spell haste.
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">PLANE OF MICHIEF</span></span>
<br />

<br />
  Ok, here is a little outline of mobs and the zone itself. The zone in to PoM is in GD, at the very south end of the river. You click a tiny little &#8216;dollhouse&#8217; in the river and that zones you in. Once inside, you&#8217;ll be standing on a glowing blue platform. It&#8217;s very safe here and a great place to kite if you like that tactic. By the way, the only zone out in PoM is a tree that you can click (just north of zone in) but it drops you in CS. For me, I generally bind in PoK and gate out when I need to. For non gaters, this is a problem. For my guide here I will only be discussing the courtyard area. This is the forest-like area that you see when you zone in.  I will not be covering the castle.
<br />

<br />
Mobs:
<br />
	Within the courtyard there are 4 types of trash mobs
<br />
1)	Skunks
<br />
2)	Shrooms
<br />
3)	Shroom Men
<br />
4)	Bixies
<br />
And also a couple special mobs
<br />
5)	Horses/unicorns
<br />
Each mob type has two variations, one generally a higher level than the other. However, the variations have a level range. For example, skunks come in two varieties, a fetid skunk (generally stronger) and a malodorous skunk. There is also a named mob for each type of mob.
<br />

<br />
Here is a list of the mobs : (this table is giving me problems)
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-size: 9px; line-height: normal"><TABLE border=1>
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold"><TR>
<br />
<TD>Type</TD>
<br />
<TD>Lower</TD>
<br />
<TD>Higher</TD>
<br />
<TD>Named</TD>
<br />
</TR></span>
<br />
<TR>
<br />
<TD>Skunks</TD>
<br />
<TD>a malodorous skunk</TD>
<br />
<TD>a fetid skunk</TD>
<br />
<TD>a funky skunk</TD>
<br />
</TR>
<br />
<TR>
<br />
<TD>Shrooms</TD>
<br />
<TD>a puckish mushroom</TD>
<br />
<TD>an exasperating mushroom</TD>
<br />
<TD>an irritation mushroom</TD>
<br />
</TR>
<br />
<TR>
<br />
<TD>Shroom Men</TD>
<br />
<TD>a merry mushroom man</TD>
<br />
<TD>a mirthful mushroom man</TD>
<br />
<TD>a maddened mushroom man</TD>
<br />
</TR>
<br />
<TR>
<br />
<TD>Bixies</TD>
<br />
<TD>a buzzing bixie</TD>
<br />
<TD>a droning bixie</TD>
<br />
<TD>Bzzibzzana</TD>
<br />
</TR>
<br />
</TABLE></span>
<br />

<br />
There is a white stallion that pops in the far North West area, along with Lithniath, a black unicorn that is for a quest (druid I believe). Lithniath is level 65.
<br />

<br />
Some GENERAL rules for these mobs:
<br />

<br />
·	Shrooms have a somewhat high Magic Resistance. They make lousy charmed pets!
<br />
·	Skunks seem to have the lowest magic resistance overall. They make great pets, plus, I mean, come on. You&#8217;re charming a big mean skunk! Isn&#8217;t that cool?
<br />
·	Bixies are rogue mobs, they generally have higher DPS, but can be somewhat MR.
<br />
·	Mob variability is great. What I mean by this is, a skunk&#8217;s MR will very a lot from malodorous skunk to malodorous skunk, and they also vary in level and hit points. You just have to charm and see what you got!
<br />
·	Shroom men are about middle of the road. Sometimes I have problem with them, sometimes not. In general, I just kill em!
<br />
·	Level range is I believe 51 to 55 with the &#8216;higher&#8217; mobs generally being the top end of this. I may not have the level range exactly right, but I know that it varies, and that some mobs are too high for the level 53 cap for Boltran&#8217;s Agacerie. The named mobs are all level 55.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">SPELL LINE UP</span></span>
<br />

<br />
At level 63, my spells have changed a great deal from when I first tried charming here (at level 56-57). I&#8217;ll explain my current spellset, and then give options for lower levels etc. By the way, the Saved Spell set options are great. I&#8217;ve created one JUST for PoM charming. That way, when I zone in, I just mem that spell set. You can even hotkey the /memspellset if you wanted. 
<br />

<br />
My Spells:
<br />
1)	Arcane Rune
<br />
2)	Howl of Tashan
<br />
3)	Dementing Visions
<br />
4)	Beckon
<br />
5)	Tepid Deeds
<br />
6)	Improved Invisibility
<br />
7)	Greater Fetter
<br />
<img src="images/smiles/icon_cool.gif" alt="icon_cool.gif" border="0" />	Rapture
<br />

<br />
Ok. So that&#8217;s what I use, but the variability can be great, depending on how you want to charm&#8230;.let&#8217;s go through them, and talk about options for lower levels/differently geared player.
<br />

<br />
1)	Rune &#8211; Of course, you won&#8217;t get Arcane Rune until level 61, but any rune will do. The advantage of Arcane is that you won&#8217;t have to target yourself and it&#8217;s 1500 pts of damage absorb. If you have to use a lower level rune, make sure you bring peridots and you can hotkey the cast to self target (/target Yourname; /cast 1; /cast ). I also keep Eldritch Rune on my hotkey list. It helps tremendously (I only have ER2) but you can survive without it. More about it later.
<br />
2)	Tash &#8211; Required. Absolutely. Charming just is no good without it. Use your highest level single target version
<br />
3)	Nuke &#8211; This one is a bit optional. Me, I like to use a nuke, though there are other options, but I find this works for me.
<br />
4)	Charm. More about this in the Strategy section. If you aren&#8217;t level 61, use Boltran&#8217;s Agacerie. It will have limitations though. See Strategy section.
<br />
5)	Slow &#8211; I use Tepid simply because the mobs die fast, and it uses very little mana. Not to mention the cast time is faster than Forlorn Deeds. Your choice though. It also helps the pet die faster, which means I can kill it too.
<br />
6)	Invis &#8211; Here is where a clicky would free up a spot. However, I don&#8217;t have a clicky, so I use the spell. The Improved Invis version is great, cuz even if I am targeting something else, it will invis me.
<br />
7)	Greater Fetter- Root is your friend, and this is a great strong root, with a MR modifier is I believe. It sticks pretty well too. More in the Strategy section.
<br />
<img src="images/smiles/icon_cool.gif" alt="icon_cool.gif" border="0" />	Rapture &#8211; Ahhh, the little used Rapture. Any mezz will do here. Glamour of Kintaz is the next best choice. It has a slight MR modifier also if I am not mistaken, and a better choice than Dazzle because of that and the shorter mezz time. I use Rapture because nothing will resist it in the courtyard, so I am guaranteed a mezz. Also, it&#8217;s only 48 seconds, which works very well. More on that soon.
<br />
There are hundreds of variations. Choose at your leisure.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">STRATEGY</span></span>
<br />

<br />
   Ok, now that we have learned how to set up, LET&#8217;S GET CHARMING ALREADY!
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Step 1 : Find a Pet:</span>
<br />
	Using the above spell set up, I have found a unique way to go about getting a pet. This is going to vary greatly depending on if you are using Beckon or Boltran&#8217;s Agacerie! With Beckon, this is no problem at all. With BA, you&#8217;ll have to manage the agro somehow, should your target be higher than 53 (the level cap for BA). Generally, if you learn the mob names and which is lower/higher, you&#8217;ll have a better chance of avoiding trying to charm a mob that is too high. Here is my method.
<br />
1)	Find a skunk or a bixie within your charming level cap (with Beckon any will work. And higher mobs are preferred if you want a tough pet. With BA, choose accordingly)
<br />
2)	Mezz it. Rapture ensures a mezz. If you are using GoK, some of the shrooms may resist. They suck.
<br />
3)	Tash it!!! This will make charm last longer! DUH! This is a must. No artistic license allowed.
<br />
4)	Charm it. Beckon will charm any trash in the courtyard. If you get a &#8216;too high for this spell&#8217; message with BA, you&#8217;ll have to deal with it&#8230;.either keep mezzing it. (assuming you&#8217;re using GoK, as Rapture has a long recast time, and you won&#8217;t be able to lockdown multiples) or Mem blur it. That&#8217;s not in my spell line up, so you may have to adjust spell sets.
<br />
5)	By this point, you&#8217;re pet should be tashed, mezzed and charmed. It&#8217;s ok that it is mezzed, if you used Rapture it should be just about to wear off. It also allows time to recharm if you get a lousy 5 second charm. While I am waiting for mezz to wear off, I click my snake stick (you can cast haste if you want to. Optional) and he is ready to go. Pet gear time also (I never use).
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Step 2 : Find a mob to kill:</span>
<br />
	Once you have your pet in tow, find a mob.
<br />
1)	Root the mob. I usually do this first, though, you could send in the pet first. I generally don&#8217;t send in pet until I slow it. See Below. With Greater Fetter, only the shrooms will occasionally give you a resist.
<br />
2)	Tash the mob. This actually makes the root stick just about full duration. It&#8217;s very little mana and finally they fixed the recast bug. It also helps prevent a slow resist.
<br />
3)	Slow the mob. I use Tepid Deeds for the lower mana cost. If you are keeping your pet a while (pet gear) use Forlorn, it&#8217;s such a long cast time, and uses much more mana.
<br />
4)	Send in your pet. This can be done really at anytime, but I like to at least be casting slow, or have it already landed before the mob is chewing up my pet.
<br />
5)	Watch with glee as your pet makes quick work of the mobs. If you charmed a &#8216;lower&#8217; mob, you&#8217;ll notice he takes quite a beating. The &#8216;higher&#8217; mobs are much tougher, but if you only have BA for charm, then this is just what you are stuck with. Overall though, they charmed/hasted pet will still chew through a slowed mob.
<br />
6)	At some point, click your Blue Ceramic Band. This ensures you don&#8217;t take that nasty exp penalty, so your pet doesn&#8217;t eat a lot of exp. It&#8217;s a good idea to wait until the mob is almost dead though, as it will most likely break root. If root breaks when you click BCB, there is always the chance of a charm breaking at the same time, and the mob AND your pet will be after you. Not good. You&#8217;ll have to re-root if root breaks. KEEP THE MOB ROOTED. You can let the mob run off if you want (does this at about 15% health) but it can run for a while, possibly aggroing other mobs. 
<br />
7)	Repeat until pet is ALMOST dead.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Step 3 : Kill your pet:</span>
<br />
  Best to do this while pet isn&#8217;t attacking a mob (in between fights).
<br />
1)	When my pet gets to about 15% or lower, I&#8217;ll cast invis, then target my pet (clicking the pet window allows you to switch targets WHILE you are casting).
<br />
2)	The pet will either come charging for you (in which case I generally root) OR
<br />
3)	The pet will wonder off in a stuper (if you have it down low enough). Good time to Nuke it! Another variation of this is to Unsuspend your Shiny Bob (assuming you have this AA and have a Shiny Bob stored) and send him in  (Assuming you have Animation Empathy) and have him finish off the pet. I find it slower though, and nuking is just a lot more fun.
<br />

<br />
So, there you have it. It&#8217;s the way that I do it. And I&#8217;ll give some variations as well, and tips for duoing etc. With this strategy you can clear just about half the courtyard before repops. A couple of tips and recommendations for this strategy:
<br />
·	Watch out for named mobs. You CAN take them with a regular charmed pet (hasted) but it&#8217;s tough, and the named mobs summon (EEP). I&#8217;m about 70/30 success on these. With a duoing partner, I&#8217;ve never failed though. There are a few nice items including a nice cloak and ring. Some is just junk. Charm breaks on a named are almost always death. The summoning sucks. Mezzing the named if charm breaks is a good strategy to deal with it.
<br />
·	Learn the mob names. If you charm the level appropriate mobs, you&#8217;ll ensure better charming, and faster exp.
<br />
·	Shrooms resist a lot. Keep em tashed and rooted.
<br />
·	LOTS of research components drop here. Great place to gather supplies. Also there are quest shroom pieces. When you gather 4, you can turn into the Treasure Hunter for a &#8216;chance&#8217; to pop a treasure chest mob. I have tried this about a half dozen times, and the stupid thing has never popped. I think it is still working though, I&#8217;m just unlucky.
<br />
·	CHARM BREAKS &#8211; I know a lot are gonna ask: &#8220;But Fading, How can I keep that mean &#8216;ole skunk from chewing my frail  up and spitting it out looking like Tasarin&#8217;s Grimoire pages?&#8221; Well, expect to die, many times. It&#8217;s been said before. You will die. However, there are some things that can turn the odds in your favor.
<br />
i.	Rune. USE IT! Eldritch rune helps too. Arcane + ER3 is best, but out of reach for some.
<br />
ii.	Keep mob rooted.
<br />
iii.	Keep your distance so you&#8217;ll have time to react.
<br />

<br />
Ok, so what do you do when it comes after you? You have several options.
<br />
1)	Remezz it. Rapture (for me) only lasts a short time, and also gives you a chance to retash/druid to resnare
<br />
2)	Color Stun &#8211; I&#8217;ve never been able to get the hang of these, but I understand the principle
<br />
3)	RUN! Use a runspeed item/spell/AA and run away from the mob, then have an extended range focus item, and a spell haste item. With those you should be able to get far enough away that you can recharm (retash if needed)
<br />
4)	Tank it! Only for the better equipped/AAed chanter. With Eldritch Rune and Arcane Rune, I &#8216;usually&#8217; can channel through my hasted pet to get a recharm or remezz off.
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline"><span style="font-weight: bold">VARIATIONS</span></span>
<br />
  Ok, I&#8217;ve tried lots of variations, this just happens to be the one I like the most. And There is NO wrong way to do this. These are just suggestions.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">METHOD : &#8220;Kill em Both&#8221;</span>
<br />
	This method is a little bit more mana intensive, but gives better exp.
<br />
·	Charm a pet using the standard charming procedure (make sure it&#8217;s tashed etc).
<br />
·	Don&#8217;t haste pet
<br />
·	Tash a mob and root it in the courtyard. Keep it rooted at all times.
<br />
·	Send in pet.
<br />
·	Both mobs will begin to tear each other up. The idea here is to have both the pet and the mob go down at the same rate. Unfortunately, some are meaner than others, so, you can slow the mob, or haste your pet at the right time (you&#8217;ll have to get the timing down, but it&#8217;s not hard). This will allow one to catch up etc on health&#8230;
<br />
·	When both are at about 15% or lower, invis yourself and be ready to root your pet.
<br />
·	Once both are rooted, nuke em both (usually a couple nukes a piece) until dead. This ensures great exp for each kill.
<br />
Works best with a snaring partner. Wizards can help out in the nuking/rooting, though druids still take the cake for their long lasting snare.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">METHOD : &#8220;Duoing with a druid&#8221;</span>
<br />
	This method is by far the best exp, and fastest I have tried. It&#8217;s just so easy it&#8217;s laughable. 
<br />
·	Use the same method I described originally, except the druid should snare while your pet is mezzed, and when the druid charms, you can mezz/tash their pet too.  The druid/ranger snare lasts 14 minutes, so a couple of charm breaks and it will still be snared.
<br />
·	Druid can heal your pets if you want to keep them, and you can haste both pets so the druid can free up a spell slot. (There is also a neat clicky animal haste item that druids can get, drops in Nadox. I bought one for my druid partner).
<br />

<br />
SO, that&#8217;s it. Suggestions are welcome. I tried containing as MUCH info as I could. And like I said, I make no guarantees and by no means is this the only way to do it. I hope you enjoyed.
<br />

<br />
If you have any feedback, comments or suggestions please send me an email at <a href="mailto:Troposfear@nc.rr.com">Troposfear@nc.rr.com</a> or send me a tell in game at tunare.Fading
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">ENJOY. CHARM THOSE SKUNKS!</span> <img src="images/smiles/icon_axe.gif" alt="icon_axe.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
