                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I use similar tactics to the ones use describe above for killing both but with a few modifications.
<br />

<br />
I always try to find two similar mobs to match them off against each other.
<br />

<br />
For charming my pet I use the following - standing away from the selected pet, tashing, running until spell gems clear and then casting charm and hoping it sticks. It's not very elegant but with high cha I rarely get a resist and it saves on mana by cutting out the mezz. Once pet is charmed I sic it on its opposite number.
<br />

<br />
As soon as the engaged mob is at 95% I cast tash, then click my bcb to guarantee my xp if my pet wins. After the bcb hits I then cast root. I used to root first but found that the BCB always broke the root so I swapped them around. I never let use the BCB late in the engagement as I want to be able to use mezz later and it is better to get the choke in early so that it doesnt interfere or I forget.
<br />

<br />
As the two mobs get low I tell the pet to guard. It will ignore me and keep fighting but it marks it place and stops it returning to me. I then start casting mezz when my pet is about 15% but keep ducking out of it unless then pet has dropped below 10% in which case I let the mezz finish. I aim to have the mezz land just as the pet gets down to 5 to 8%.
<br />

<br />
As I have already told the pet to guard it will stay next to the mob instead of lumbering back to me. However higher level mezzes have a memblur component and there is a risk that the mob will explosively heal so I instantly cast root on it after the mezz to ensure I retain agro and it won't heal.
<br />

<br />
I then cast dispell on the pet and edge back as it lunges for me. Normamly it lunges for a few yards, suddenly notices its somewhat hurt and it turns to saunter off allowing me to finish it with a nuke. However sometimes it will suddenly heal itself to 35% and keep charging so I quickly slap a mezz on it and charm the injured mob to use it agains t my expet. 
<br />

<br />
If I've killed my pet I then check the mobs health, if its below 15% I will just nuke it to death, if it is above 15% I will use it as a new pet.
<br />

<br />
Either way I always kill my pet before I kill the mob it was attacking. My preference is to arrange it so that I go into a fight with a pet already at 50% hp so that I can break it down faster, kill it then use the mob its been chewing on as my new pet to go onto the next one in turn.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
